AWS Cloud Lab 5 – DynamoDB Integration with EC2
1. Objective
To connect an Amazon EC2 instance to DynamoDB using an IAM role and perform CRUD operations securely without embedding AWS credentials.

2. DynamoDB Table Details
Attribute	Description
Table Name	LabTable
Partition Key	id
Datatypes Used	String, Number, Boolean, List, Map

Sample Item Inserted:
{
  "id": 2,
  "name": "User2",
  "isActive": true,
  "tags": ["tag1","tag2"],
  "metadata": {"role":"admin"}
}

3. IAM Role Configuration
Role Name: EC2-DynamoDB-Role
Policy Attached: AmazonDynamoDBFullAccess
Purpose: Allows EC2 to access DynamoDB without AWS keys.

Steps Taken:
Created IAM role for EC2 in AWS IAM.
Attached AmazonDynamoDBFullAccess policy.
Attached the role to EC2 instance.

4. CRUD Operations
All commands executed from EC2 terminal.
Create Item:
aws dynamodb put-item --table-name LabTable --item '{"id":{"S":"2"},"name":{"S":"User2"}}'

Read Item:
aws dynamodb get-item --table-name LabTable --key '{"id":{"S":"2"}}'

Update Item:
aws dynamodb update-item --table-name LabTable --key '{"id":{"S":"2"}}' --update-expression "SET name = :n" --expression-attribute-values '{":n":{"S":"UpdatedUser"}}'

Delete Item:
aws dynamodb delete-item --table-name LabTable --key '{"id":{"S":"2"}}'

5. Security Considerations
EC2 accesses DynamoDB via IAM role – no hard-coded credentials.
Role attached ensures least privilege for lab operations.
Policy used: AmazonDynamoDBFullAccess .
